Important Entry Points
- cli.js: This is the entry point for the command-line interface. It defines the commands and options available to the user and handles user input.
- app.js: This file contains the core logic for task management, including validation, task creation, and updating. It interacts with the storage.js file to perform CRUD operations on tasks.
- storage.js: This file is responsible for loading tasks from the tasks.json file and performing CRUD operations on the tasks. It provides functions to add, update, delete, and retrieve tasks.
- model.js: This is the Domain Entry POint. IT defines the codre entity used everywhere. it controls tasks behavioues markAsDone(),update(), isOverdue() etc. It also defines the TaskPriority and TaskStatus enums which are used to categorize tasks based on their priority and status.

KEY COMPONENTS AND RESPONSIBILITIES
- cli layer(cli.js): Defines all cli commands using Command.js and handles user interactions. It serves as the interface between the user and the application logic.. it creates, lists, status, priority, due show, delete. etc
- app layer(app.js): Contains the core logic for task management, including validation, task creation, and updating. It interacts with the storage layer to perform CRUD operations on tasks. It also contains the business logic for handling tasks, such as marking tasks as done or checking if a task is overdue.
- storage layer(storage.js): Responsible for loading tasks from the tasks.json file and performing CRUD operations on the tasks. It provides functions to add, update, delete, and retrieve tasks. It acts as a data access layer that abstracts away the details of how tasks are stored and retrieved.
- model layer(models.js): Defines the data structures for tasks, priorities, and statuses. It includes the Task class, which represents a task entity with properties such as id, title, description, priority, status, and due date. It also defines the TaskPriority and TaskStatus enums, which are used to categorize tasks based on their priority and status. The model layer encapsulates the core entities and their behaviors, providing a clear representation of the domain concepts in the application.
- tasks.json: This file serves as a simple data store for the tasks. It is used to persist the tasks created by the user and allows for retrieval and manipulation of tasks across different sessions of the application. The storage layer interacts with this file to perform CRUD operations on the tasks, ensuring that the data is saved and retrieved correctly.
- uuid package: This npm package is used to generate unique task IDs. It ensures that each task created has a unique identifier, which is essential for managing tasks effectively and avoiding conflicts when performing CRUD operations on tasks. The uuid package provides a simple and reliable way to generate unique IDs for tasks in the application.


